n second-wave feminism, the civil rights movement, and multicultural education increasingly influenced which books were taught. This edition also considers how readers might approach the book today, when new archaeological evidence is emerging about the “Lone Woman of San Nicolas Island,” on whom O’Dell’s story is based, and Native peoples are engaged in the reclamation of indigenous histories and ongoing struggles for political sovereignty.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aIndians of North AmericavFiction. 0aIndians of North AmericavJuvenile fiction. 0aIslandsvFiction. 0aSurvivalvFiction. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  aamerican literature.  acalifornia indians.  acalifornia natives.  achildren s literature.  achildrens lit.  achildrens literature.  acolonial histories.  ahistorical fiction.  aindigenous americans.  aindigenous literature.  aindigenous people.  ajuvenile fiction.  alone woman of san nicolas island.  amulticultural literature.  anative american literature.  anative american stories.  anative american studies.  anative american.  anative americans.  anative californians.  anative literature.  anative peoples.  anewbery winner.  asurvival narratives.1 aGoldberg, Carole, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVellanoweth, René L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z97831106675470 cprintz978052028937640uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052096406840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520964068423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520964068/original  a978-3-11-066754-7  University of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_FAO  